UI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T-", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7666158676147461, "span": {"begin": 455, "end": 457}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7052"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tissue transglutaminase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9796898365020752, "span": {"begin": 693, "end": 716}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7052"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TG2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9882489442825317, "span": {"begin": 718, "end": 721}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005973"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glutamine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9896092414855957, "span": {"begin": 748, "end": 757}}, {"id": ["mesh:D018698"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glutamic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9925103783607483, "span": {"begin": 772, "end": 785}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3120"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HLA-DQ2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9955156445503235, "span": {"begin": 950, "end": 957}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3130"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HLA-DQ8", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9939458966255188, "span": {"begin": 961, "end": 968}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002446", "mim:212750"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "celiac disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999999463558197, "span": {"begin": 1140, "end": 1154}}], "text": "Celiac disease is an intestinal disorder triggered by gluten ingestion. It exclusively occurs in individuals who are positive for HLA-DQ2, HLA-DQ8, or both (Sollid, 1989; Dieterich, 1997). In patients with celiac disease, CD4+ T cells specifically recognize complexes formed between HLA-DQ2/8 molecules and modified gluten peptides (Molberg, 1997; Meresse, 2004; Sollid, 2012).&nbsp;The formation of these HLA-DQ2/8-gluten complexes is a prerequisite for T-cell activation (Molberg, 1998; Arentz-Hansen, 2000; Vader, 2002).  Upon gluten ingestion, proteolytic fragments are generated through enzymatic cleavage in the upper gastrointestinal tract. These fragments are subsequently modified by tissue transglutaminase (TG2), which converts specific glutamine residues into glutamic acid (Dieterich, 1997; Molberg, 1998). This modification introduces negatively charged residues, which are crucial for high-affinity binding of the modified peptides to HLA-DQ2 or HLA-DQ8, as these molecules preferentially bind peptides with such negatively charged residues (Vader, 2003; Sollid, 2012). This process underlies the immune response observed in celiac disease.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:59:46 +0000 2026"}